snippet.textDisplay: I owned a 2008 e93 M3 BMW for 10 years and traded it in last year.  When I got it, it was my dream car.  Driving it with the roof down and ripping the engine down a country road was the best way to experience this car.  I loved the way it looked and the way it drove.   But after time, all of its shortcomings really got to me and I traded it in.  While I didn't have rod bearing issues, I had to replace both actuators which were ridiculously overpriced.  Also the cheap leather lining that covers most of the interior was peeling off the steering wheel and the small holders in the car door.  The leather seats themselves were also starting to deteriorate. There were simply too many problems that I simply couldn't justify it being my daily driver any longer.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm going to solve the "up arrow" riddle on the key: When you opened the car, the locking knobs (or whatever you call them) on the doors go up. Hence the arrow.

Also: in all his years reviewing BMWs, has Doug never learned that the turn signals have 2 stages? One light tap and it blinks 3x for lane changes and a bigger push for staying on until you completed your turn. You can turn the latter off by simply performing a light tap in either direction. It's like a better camera's shutter button where a light tap just activates focus.
I actually prefer this a lot compared to the "traditional" way.

snippet.textDisplay:
You tap the stalk again at the same direction you're indicating to turn it of manually. ;)

Was a bit confused about the turn signals at first on my e91 but really learned to like them after a few weeks. Now, whenever I drive anything else I get frustrated at the conventional turn signals.

Because it always returns to the middle, changing lanes back and forth is a breeze, and you never get the "I was supposed to tap for lane change but pushed too far and now the indicator is on" -situation.

Sad to hear newer models not having this, if I ever decide to upgrade. :/

snippet.textDisplay: Explanation on the dial for the air vents. That doesn’t “override” your temp. It determines how hot or cold the air that blows on you will be while still trying to achieve the temp you set the car to be. Example if I want it to be 72 that can be done by blowing 100° air on me or 72° air. Also to note it does nothing as far as I’ve ever been able to tell over the years if you set the temp to max heat or max cool

snippet.textDisplay:
Good lord, that was painful. If you want to see someone who knows cars discuss this thing, find Savagegeese's review.


1 - Now let me see... When you unlock a car, what direction do the door lock buttons go?


2 - If you want to race, you don't get the manual. The DCT is faster, which is generally what one looks for when one races.


3 - Those center vent controls have been in almost every BMW since the '80s. They're great for getting cool air on your face when you have the heat cranked up in the winter. I wish more cars had 'em.


4 - The 2nd post on the mirror is because the mirror was designed in a wind tunnel. The whole shape was designed to reduce wind noise and drag.



I instructed in one of these at COTA a few years ago. It had a Billy Boat exhaust, and was probably the best sounding car I've ever been in.

snippet.textDisplay: I ordered my E92 M3 Competition in Alpine White with cabin fiber aero and the inconel exhaust.  I took delivery in December of 2012 and I still own the car.  At idle the engine/exhaust is so angry and so glorious due to the aggressive cams.   It belts out a low rumble that's part muscle car, part race car.  Using the fun peddle in anger sends the tach to the 8,300 RPM redline real damn quick, causing the engine to go from growl to sheik.  This car has tapped into my joy center.  I am elated every time I get behind the wheel.
